Some estimate of the importance os the Licinio—Sextian laws may now be made. As has been often pointed out, they indicate a combination of the richer and poorer plebeians for the purpose of wringing from the patricians advantages which could only be gained by a united effort. Many plebeians were well enough off materially‚ and no doubt exercised their ad- vantage over debtors to the full as cruelly as any of the patricians did.
